why is that

The issue with the footer not sticking to the bottom of the page in your `headshot.jsx` file is likely due to the content inside the `<div>` element with the inline styles `display: 'flex'`, `justifyContent: 'center'`, `alignItems: 'center'`, and `minHeight: '100vh'`.

When you set `minHeight: '100vh'` on that `<div>`, it ensures that the container takes up the full height of the viewport. However, if the content inside that container exceeds the viewport height, it will push the footer down, causing it to not stick to the bottom.

To fix this, you can modify the structure of your `headshot.jsx` file to use a flex layout similar to the `App` component in the previous example. Here's how you can update your code:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { Card, Form, Alert, Container, Row, Col, Button, Carousel } from 'react-bootstrap';
import Navbar from '../../components/Navbar/Navbar.jsx';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer/Footer.jsx';
import { Stack } from "@mui/joy";
import './headshot.scss';
import AWS from 'aws-sdk';

// ... (rest of the code remains the same)

function Headshot() {
    // ... (state variables and functions remain the same)

    return (
        <Stack sx={{ minHeight: '100vh' }}>
            <Navbar />
            <Stack sx={{ flexGrow: 1 }}>
                <div id="headshot" style={{ maxWidth: '800px', width: '100%', margin: '0 auto' }}>
                    {/* ... (rest of the content inside the "headshot" div) */}
                </div>
            </Stack>
            <Footer />
        </Stack>
    );
}

export default Headshot;
```

In this updated code:

1. The outermost `<Stack>` component is used to create a flex container with a minimum height of `100vh`.
2. The `<Navbar />` component is placed as the first child of the outermost `<Stack>`.
3. The main content of the `headshot.jsx` file is wrapped inside another `<Stack>` component with `flexGrow: 1` to make it expand and fill the remaining vertical space.
4. The `<Footer />` component is placed as the last child of the outermost `<Stack>`.

By making these changes, the footer should stick to the bottom of the page, even when the content inside the `headshot.jsx` file exceeds the viewport height.

Remember to adjust the styling of the content inside the `"headshot"` div as needed to ensure proper spacing and alignment.

I see. If the images you added are causing the issue, you can try wrapping the content inside the `"headshot"` div with a `<div>` that has a fixed height and uses `overflow-y: auto` to make it scrollable when the content exceeds the available height. This way, the footer will remain at the bottom of the page, and the content will be scrollable within the fixed-height container.

Here's how you can modify your code:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { Card, Form, Alert, Container, Row, Col, Button, Carousel } from 'react-bootstrap';
import Navbar from '../../components/Navbar/Navbar.jsx';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer/Footer.jsx';
import { Stack } from "@mui/joy";
import './headshot.scss';
import AWS from 'aws-sdk';

// ... (rest of the code remains the same)

function Headshot() {
    // ... (state variables and functions remain the same)

    return (
        <Stack sx={{ minHeight: '100vh' }}>
            <Navbar />
            <Stack sx={{ flexGrow: 1, overflow: 'hidden' }}>
                <div style={{ height: 'calc(100vh - 64px)', overflowY: 'auto' }}>
                    <div id="headshot" style={{ maxWidth: '800px', width: '100%', margin: '0 auto' }}>
                        {/* ... (rest of the content inside the "headshot" div) */}
                    </div>
                </div>
            </Stack>
            <Footer />
        </Stack>
    );
}

export default Headshot;
```

In this updated code:

1. The `<Stack>` component that wraps the main content is given `overflow: 'hidden'` to hide any overflowing content.
2. Inside the `<Stack>`, a new `<div>` is added with a fixed height of `calc(100vh - 64px)`. This assumes that the navbar has a height of `64px`. Adjust this value according to your navbar's actual height.
3. The new `<div>` is given `overflowY: 'auto'` to make it scrollable when the content exceeds the available height.
4. The `"headshot"` div is placed inside the scrollable `<div>`.

With these changes, the content inside the `"headshot"` div will be scrollable within the fixed-height container, and the footer will remain pinned at the bottom of the page.

Make sure to adjust the height calculation (`calc(100vh - 64px)`) based on the actual height of your navbar to ensure proper spacing.

