MAKE THE IMAGES SMALLER AND SIDE BY SIDE (RATHER THAN ON TOP OF EACH OTHER)

To make the images smaller and display them side by side, you can modify the Carousel component and adjust the styling. Here's the updated code:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { Alert, Button, Card, Carousel, Container, Form, Row, Col } from 'react-bootstrap';
import Navbar from '../../components/Navbar/Navbar.jsx';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer/Footer.jsx';
import './headshot.scss';

function Headshot() {
    // ... (rest of the code remains the same)

    return (
        <>
            <Navbar />
            <Container className="headshot-container d-flex align-items-center justify-content-center text-center" style={{ minHeight: '100vh', flexDirection: 'column' }}>
                {/* Adjusted Carousel for smaller images side by side */}
                <Carousel className="mb-4 headshot-carousel" indicators={false} controls={false} wrap={true} interval={3000}>
                    <Carousel.Item>
                        <Row>
                            {imageUrls.slice(0, 3).map((url, index) => (
                                <Col key={index} xs={4}>
                                    <img className="d-block w-100" src={url} alt={`Image ${index}`} style={{ objectFit: 'cover', height: '200px' }} />
                                </Col>
                            ))}
                        </Row>
                    </Carousel.Item>
                    <Carousel.Item>
                        <Row>
                            {imageUrls.slice(3, 6).map((url, index) => (
                                <Col key={index} xs={4}>
                                    <img className="d-block w-100" src={url} alt={`Image ${index + 3}`} style={{ objectFit: 'cover', height: '200px' }} />
                                </Col>
                            ))}
                        </Row>
                    </Carousel.Item>
                    <Carousel.Item>
                        <Row>
                            {imageUrls.slice(6, 9).map((url, index) => (
                                <Col key={index} xs={4}>
                                    <img className="d-block w-100" src={url} alt={`Image ${index + 6}`} style={{ objectFit: 'cover', height: '200px' }} />
                                </Col>
                            ))}
                        </Row>
                    </Carousel.Item>
                </Carousel>

                {/* Additional content here... */}

                {/* ... (rest of the code remains the same) */}
            </Container>
            <Footer />
        </>
    );
}

export default Headshot;
```

In this updated code:

- The `Carousel` component is modified to display smaller images side by side.
- Inside each `Carousel.Item`, a `Row` component is used to create a row of images.
- The `imageUrls` array is sliced into chunks of 3 images using `slice()` to display 3 images per row.
- Each image is wrapped in a `Col` component with `xs={4}` to set the column width to 4 out of 12 (1/3 of the row width).
- The `style` prop is added to each image to set `objectFit: 'cover'` and `height: '200px'` to ensure the images maintain their aspect ratio and have a fixed height.

With these changes, the carousel will display smaller images side by side, with 3 images per row. The images will have a fixed height of 200 pixels and will maintain their aspect ratio using `object-fit: cover`.

Make sure to adjust the `height` value in the `style` prop if you want to change the height of the images.

