Certainly! Here's the updated code with email validation and a friendly user message:

```jsx
const [email, setEmail] = useState('');
const [emailError, setEmailError] = useState('');

// ... (rest of the code)

const validateEmail = (email) => {
    // Simple email validation regex pattern
    const emailPattern = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/;
    return emailPattern.test(email);
};

const handleEmailChange = (e) => {
    const newEmail = e.target.value;
    setEmail(newEmail);

    if (newEmail.trim() === '') {
        setEmailError('');
    } else if (!validateEmail(newEmail)) {
        setEmailError('E-mail not valid');
    } else {
        setEmailError('');
    }
};

// ... (rest of the code)

{/* Email form */}
<Card className="email-card my-4" style={{ width: '100%', maxWidth: '600px', backgroundColor: '#f8f9fa' }}>
    <Card.Body>
        <Card.Title className="mb-4" style={{ color: 'black' }}>Enter Your Email</Card.Title>
        <Form.Group controlId="emailInput">
            <Form.Control
                type="email"
                placeholder="Enter your email"
                value={email}
                onChange={handleEmailChange}
                style={{ borderRadius: '25px', padding: '10px 20px', color: 'black' }}
            />
            {emailError && (
                <Form.Text className="text-danger">{emailError}</Form.Text>
            )}
        </Form.Group>
    </Card.Body>
</Card>

{/* "Submit" button */}
<Button
    variant="primary"
    onClick={handleSubmit}
    disabled={selectedFiles.length === 0 || selectedFiles.length > 20 || loading || !email || emailError}
    className="mt-2"
    style={{ backgroundColor: '#007bff', borderColor: '#007bff', borderRadius: '25px', padding: '10px 30px', color: 'black' }}
>
    {loading ? 'Processing...' : 'Submit'}
</Button>
```

The changes made:
- Added a new state variable `emailError` to store the email validation error message.
- Created a `validateEmail` function that uses a simple email validation regex pattern to check if the email is valid.
- Updated the `handleEmailChange` function to validate the email whenever the input value changes. If the email is empty, it clears the error message. If the email is invalid, it sets the error message to "E-mail not valid". Otherwise, it clears the error message.
- Added a conditional rendering of the error message below the email input field using `Form.Text` component with the `text-danger` class for red text color.
- Updated the `disabled` prop of the "Submit" button to include the condition `emailError` to disable the button if there is an email validation error.

Now, when the user enters an invalid email, a friendly error message "E-mail not valid" will be displayed below the email input field, and the "Submit" button will be disabled until a valid email is entered.

