                &lt;/Form.Group&gt;
                &lt;Button
                    variant=&quot;primary&quot;
                    onClick={handleSubmit}
                    disabled={selectedFiles.length === 0 || selectedFiles.length &gt; 20 || loading || !email || emailError || !isPayingUser}
                    className=&quot;mt-2&quot;
                    style={{
                        backgroundColor: '#747fe7',
                        borderColor: '#14b0e2',
                        borderRadius: '25px',
                        padding: '10px 30px',
                        color: 'black'
                    }}
                &gt;
                    {loading ? 'Processing...' : 'Submit'}
                &lt;/Button&gt;
            &lt;/Container&gt;
            &lt;Footer/&gt;
        &lt;/&gt;
    );
}

export default Headshot;


I NEED A FEW LAST THINGS FROM YOU: 
1 - IN THIS FILE I WANT TO TAKE THE IMAGES THE USER UPLOADS (E.g if he uploaded 6 images) i would create a folder called with the corresponding users  email at my s3 bucket
2- I want to send the images directly to my s3 bucket from here so that I can call the api in another file

To upload the images directly to your S3 bucket from the React component and create a folder with the user's email, you can use the AWS SDK for JavaScript. Here's how you can modify the code to achieve this:

1. Install the AWS SDK for JavaScript:

```bash
npm install aws-sdk
```

2. Configure AWS credentials:

Create a file named `aws-config.js` in your project's `src` directory and add the following code:

```javascript
import AWS from 'aws-sdk';

AWS.config.update({
  accessKeyId: 'YOUR_ACCESS_KEY',
  secretAccessKey: 'YOUR_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY',
  region: 'YOUR_AWS_REGION',
});

export default AWS;
```

Replace `'YOUR_ACCESS_KEY'`, `'YOUR_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY'`, and `'YOUR_AWS_REGION'` with your actual AWS credentials and region.

3. Modify the `handleSubmit` function in the `Headshot` component:

```javascript
import AWS from '../../aws-config';

// ...

const handleSubmit = async () => {
  if (selectedFiles.length === 4) {
    setErrorMessage('Please select at least 4 images.');
    return;
  }
  if (selectedFiles.length > 15) {
    setErrorMessage('You can upload a maximum of 15 images.');
    return;
  }

  setLoading(true);

  try {
    const s3 = new AWS.S3();

    // Create a folder with the user's email in the S3 bucket
    const folderName = email;
    const folderKey = `${folderName}/`;

    // Upload each image to the user's folder in the S3 bucket
    const uploadPromises = selectedFiles.map((file, index) => {
      const fileName = `image_${index + 1}.jpg`;
      const fileKey = `${folderKey}${fileName}`;

      return s3.upload({
        Bucket: 'YOUR_S3_BUCKET_NAME',
        Key: fileKey,
        Body: file,
        ContentType: file.type,
      }).promise();
    });

    await Promise.all(uploadPromises);

    // Reset form after successful submission
    setSelectedFiles([]);
    setEmail('');
    setGender('man');
    setIsPayingUser(false);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error uploading images:', error);
    // Handle the error case
  }

  setLoading(false);
};
```

Replace `'YOUR_S3_BUCKET_NAME'` with the name of your S3 bucket.

In this modified code:
- The AWS SDK is imported from the `aws-config.js` file.
- Inside the `handleSubmit` function, an instance of the `AWS.S3` class is created.
- A folder with the user's email is created in the S3 bucket using the `folderName` and `folderKey` variables.
- The `uploadPromises` array is created by mapping over the `selectedFiles` array and creating an upload promise for each file using `s3.upload()`.
- The `Promise.all()` method is used to wait for all the upload promises to resolve before resetting the form.

With these modifications, when the user submits the form, the selected images will be uploaded to a folder in your S3 bucket named after the user's email. You can then access these images from another file by referencing the appropriate S3 bucket and folder path.

Remember to replace `'YOUR_ACCESS_KEY'`, `'YOUR_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY'`, `'YOUR_AWS_REGION'`, and `'YOUR_S3_BUCKET_NAME'` with your actual AWS credentials, region, and S3 bucket name.

The error message indicates that the AWS SDK is missing the necessary credentials to authenticate and access your AWS resources.
To resolve this issue, you have a few options:
1. Set the AWS credentials as environment variables: - Open your terminal or command prompt. - Set the following environment variables with your AWS access key ID and secret access key: ``` export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=YOUR_ACCESS_KEY export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=YOUR_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY ``` - Replace `YOUR_ACCESS_KEY` and `YOUR_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY` with your actual AWS credentials.
2. Use AWS shared credentials file: - Create a file named `credentials` in the `~/.aws/` directory (on Linux/Mac) or `%UserProfile%\.aws\` directory (on Windows). - Add the following lines to the `credentials` file: ``` [default] aws_access_key_id = YOUR_ACCESS_KEY aws_secret_access_key = YOUR_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY ``` - Replace `YOUR_ACCESS_KEY` and `YOUR_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY` with your actual AWS credentials.
3. Use AWS configuration file: - Create a file named `config` in the `~/.aws/` directory (on Linux/Mac) or `%UserProfile%\.aws\` directory (on Windows). - Add the following lines to the `config` file: ``` [default] region = YOUR_AWS_REGION ``` - Replace `YOUR_AWS_REGION` with your actual AWS region (e.g., `us-east-1`). - If you are using this method, make sure to set the `AWS_SDK_LOAD_CONFIG` environment variable to `1` before running your application: ``` export AWS_SDK_LOAD_CONFIG=1 ```
After setting up the credentials using one of the above methods, update your `aws-config.js` file to load the credentials accordingly:
```javascript import AWS from 'aws-sdk';
// Option 1: Load credentials from environment variables AWS.config.update({ accessKeyId: process.env.AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID, secretAccessKey: process.env.AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY, region: 'YOUR_AWS_REGION', });
// Option 2: Load credentials from shared credentials file // AWS.config.credentials = new AWS.SharedIniFileCredentials(); // AWS.config.update({ region: 'YOUR_AWS_REGION' });
// Option 3: Load credentials from AWS configuration file // AWS.config.update({ region: 'YOUR_AWS_REGION' });
export default AWS; ```
Uncomment the appropriate option based on the method you used to set up the credentials.
Make sure to replace `'YOUR_AWS_REGION'` with your actual AWS region.
After setting up the credentials correctly, the AWS SDK should be able to authenticate and access your AWS resources without the "Missing credentials" error.

