To upload multiple files selected by the user to Firebase Storage, you can modify the `handleSubmit` function in your `headshot.jsx` file. Here's the updated code:

```jsx
const handleSubmit = async (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();

  if (selectedFiles.length < 4) {
    setErrorMessage('Please select at least 4 images.');
    return;
  }

  if (selectedFiles.length > 15) {
    setErrorMessage('You can upload a maximum of 15 images.');
    return;
  }

  if (selectedFiles.length > 0 && gender) {
    const uploadPromises = selectedFiles.map((file) => {
      const storageRef = ref(storage, file.name);
      return uploadBytes(storageRef, file);
    });

    try {
      await Promise.all(uploadPromises);
      console.log('Images uploaded successfully');
      alert('Images uploaded successfully.');
      // Reset the form after successful upload
      setGender('');
      setSelectedFiles([]);
    } catch (err) {
      console.error('Error uploading images:', err);
      alert('Error uploading images. Please try again.');
    }
  }
};
```

In this updated code:

1. The `selectedFiles` state variable is used instead of `selectedImage` to handle multiple file uploads.

2. The condition `if (selectedFiles.length < 4)` checks if the user has selected at least 4 images. If not, an error message is set using `setErrorMessage`, and the function returns.

3. The condition `if (selectedFiles.length > 15)` checks if the user has selected more than 15 images. If so, an error message is set using `setErrorMessage`, and the function returns.

4. Inside the `if (selectedFiles.length > 0 && gender)` block:
   - The `uploadPromises` array is created using `map` to iterate over each selected file.
   - For each file, a storage reference is created using `ref(storage, file.name)`.
   - The `uploadBytes` function is called with the storage reference and the file, and the resulting promise is added to the `uploadPromises` array.

5. The `Promise.all` function is used to wait for all the upload promises to resolve.
   - If all the uploads are successful, a success message is logged and displayed using `alert`.
   - The form is reset by setting `gender` to an empty string and `selectedFiles` to an empty array.

6. If an error occurs during the upload process, an error message is logged and displayed using `alert`.

Make sure you have the necessary state variables and functions in your component, such as `selectedFiles`, `setSelectedFiles`, `gender`, `setGender`, and `setErrorMessage`.

Also, ensure that you have the Firebase Storage configuration properly set up and imported, as shown in the previous examples.

With these modifications, your `handleSubmit` function will now take the files uploaded by the user and upload them to your Firebase Storage.

I apologize for the confusion. It seems that the `uploadBytes` function is not imported correctly. Make sure you have imported the `uploadBytes` function from the `firebase/storage` module.

Here's the corrected code with the proper import statement:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { Alert, Button, Card, Carousel, Container, Form } from 'react-bootstrap';
import Navbar from '../../components/Navbar/Navbar.jsx';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer/Footer.jsx';
import './headshot.scss';
import { ref, uploadBytes } from 'firebase/storage';
import { storage } from './firebaseConfig';

function Headshot() {
  const [gender, setGender] = useState('');
  const [selectedFiles, setSelectedFiles] = useState([]);
  const [errorMessage, setErrorMessage] = useState('');

  const handleFileChange = (e) => {
    setSelectedFiles(Array.from(e.target.files));
  };

  const handleSubmit = async (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    if (selectedFiles.length < 4) {
      setErrorMessage('Please select at least 4 images.');
      return;
    }

    if (selectedFiles.length > 15) {
      setErrorMessage('You can upload a maximum of 15 images.');
      return;
    }

    if (selectedFiles.length > 0 && gender) {
      const uploadPromises = selectedFiles.map((file) => {
        const storageRef = ref(storage, file.name);
        return uploadBytes(storageRef, file);
      });

      try {
        await Promise.all(uploadPromises);
        console.log('Images uploaded successfully');
        alert('Images uploaded successfully.');
        // Reset the form after successful upload
        setGender('');
        setSelectedFiles([]);
      } catch (err) {
        console.error('Error uploading images:', err);
        alert('Error uploading images. Please try again.');
      }
    }
  };

  return (
    <>
      {/* ... */}
      <Form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
        <Form.Group controlId="genderSelect" className="mb-3" style={{ display: 'inline-block' }}>
          <Form.Label>Select Your Gender</Form.Label>
          <Form.Select value={gender} onChange={(e) => setGender(e.target.value)} style={{ width: 'auto' }}>
            <option value="">Choose</option>
            <option value="man">Man</option>
            <option value="woman">Woman</option>
          </Form.Select>
        </Form.Group>
        {/* ... */}
        <Form.Group controlId="imageUpload" className="mb-3">
          <Form.Label>Select Images</Form.Label>
          <Form.Control type="file" multiple onChange={handleFileChange} />
        </Form.Group>
        {errorMessage && <Alert variant="danger">{errorMessage}</Alert>}
        <Button type="submit" disabled={selectedFiles.length === 0 || !gender}>Upload Images</Button>
      </Form>
      {/* ... */}
    </>
  );
}

export default Headshot;
```

In this corrected code:

1. The `uploadBytes` function is imported from the `firebase/storage` module along with the `ref` function.

2. The `selectedFiles` state variable is used to store the selected files, and the `handleFileChange` function is updated to handle multiple file selection using `Array.from(e.target.files)`.

3. The `errorMessage` state variable is added to store and display error messages.

4. The rest of the code remains the same, using the `uploadBytes` function to upload each selected file to Firebase Storage.

Make sure you have the `firebase/storage` module installed and the Firebase Storage configuration properly set up in your `firebaseConfig.js` file.

