Certainly! If you want to allow non-authenticated users to upload files to Firebase Storage, you can modify the security rules to grant write access to everyone, including unauthenticated users. However, please note that this approach is not recommended for production applications as it allows anyone to write to your storage bucket.

Here's how you can update the Firebase Storage security rules to allow write access for everyone:

1. Go to the Firebase Console (https://console.firebase.google.com/).

2. Select your project.

3. In the left-hand menu, click on "Storage" to access the Firebase Storage section.

4. Click on the "Rules" tab at the top of the page.

5. Modify the security rules to allow write access for everyone. Replace the existing rules with the following:

```
rules_version = '2';
service firebase.storage {
  match /b/{bucket}/o {
    match /{allPaths=**} {
      allow read, write: if true;
    }
  }
}
```

These rules allow read and write access to all paths in your storage bucket for everyone, including unauthenticated users, by using the condition `if true`.

6. Click on the "Publish" button to save and apply the new rules.

After updating the security rules, anyone, including non-authenticated users, will be able to upload files to your Firebase Storage bucket.

