To retrieve the image URLs from your Firebase Storage instead of the Amazon S3 bucket, you can use the Firebase Storage SDK and the `listAll` method to get a list of files in a specific folder. Here's how you can modify the code:

```jsx
import { ref, listAll, getDownloadURL } from 'firebase/storage';
import { storage } from './firebaseConfig';

// ...

const fetchImageUrls = async () => {
  const folderRef = ref(storage, 'samples/');

  try {
    const listResult = await listAll(folderRef);
    const urlPromises = listResult.items.map((itemRef) => getDownloadURL(itemRef));
    const urls = await Promise.all(urlPromises);
    setImageUrls(urls);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching image URLs:', error);
  }
};

useEffect(() => {
  fetchImageUrls();
}, []);

// ...
```

Here's how the modified code works:

1. Import the necessary functions from the Firebase Storage SDK: `ref`, `listAll`, and `getDownloadURL`.

2. Create a new function called `fetchImageUrls` that will retrieve the image URLs from Firebase Storage.

3. Inside the `fetchImageUrls` function:
   - Create a reference to the "samples" folder in your Firebase Storage using `ref(storage, 'samples/')`.
   - Use the `listAll` method to get a list of all files in the "samples" folder.
   - Map over the `listResult.items` array and create an array of promises using `getDownloadURL` for each file reference.
   - Use `Promise.all` to wait for all the download URL promises to resolve.
   - Set the resolved URLs to the `imageUrls` state using `setImageUrls`.

4. Use the `useEffect` hook to call the `fetchImageUrls` function when the component mounts. This will trigger the retrieval of image URLs from Firebase Storage.

5. The `imageUrls` state will now contain an array of download URLs for the images in the "samples" folder of your Firebase Storage.

Make sure you have the necessary imports and Firebase Storage configuration set up correctly in your component file.

With these modifications, the code will fetch the image URLs from your Firebase Storage instead of the Amazon S3 bucket. The `imageUrls` state will be populated with the download URLs of the images in the "samples" folder.

Note: Make sure that the "samples" folder exists in your Firebase Storage and contains the desired images. Also, ensure that the storage security rules are configured to allow read access to the "samples" folder for the appropriate users or for public access, depending on your requirements.

