To display the images side by side with a slider (carousel), you can modify the JSX code in your main component and update the CSS accordingly. Here's the updated code:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import { Container, Carousel } from 'react-bootstrap';
import Navbar from './Navbar';
import './Carousel.css';

const images = [
  'image1.jpg',
  'image2.jpg',
  'image3.jpg',
  // Add more image URLs as needed
];

const MainComponent = () => {
  const [index, setIndex] = useState(0);

  const handleSelect = (selectedIndex, e) => {
    setIndex(selectedIndex);
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    const timer = setInterval(() => {
      setIndex((prevIndex) => (prevIndex + 1) % images.length);
    }, 3000);

    return () => {
      clearInterval(timer);
    };
  }, []);

  return (
    <>
      <Navbar />
      <Container
        className="headshot-container d-flex align-items-center justify-content-center text-center"
        style={{ minHeight: '100vh', flexDirection: 'column' }}
      >
        <div className="text-center mb-5">
          <h2 style={{ color: 'purple', fontWeight: 'bold' }}>
            Photorealistic Generated Headshots
          </h2>
        </div>
        <div className="carousel-container">
          <Carousel
            activeIndex={index}
            onSelect={handleSelect}
            indicators={false}
            controls={true}
            wrap={true}
            interval={3000}
            className="mb-4 headshot-carousel"
          >
            {images.map((url, i) => (
              <Carousel.Item key={i} className="carousel-item">
                <div className="d-flex justify-content-center">
                  {images.slice(i, i + 3).map((imgUrl, j) => (
                    <img
                      key={j}
                      className="d-inline-block mx-2"
                      src={imgUrl}
                      alt={`Image ${i + j + 1}`}
                    />
                  ))}
                </div>
              </Carousel.Item>
            ))}
          </Carousel>
        </div>
      </Container>
    </>
  );
};

export default MainComponent;
```

And here's the updated CSS code (`Carousel.css`):

```css
.carousel-container {
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 800px;
  margin: 0 auto;
}

.headshot-carousel {
  width: 100%;
  height: auto;
}

.carousel-item {
  height: 200px; /* Adjust the height as needed */
}

.carousel-item img {
  width: auto;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: cover;
}
```

Explanation:
- In the JSX code, within each `Carousel.Item`, a `div` with the classes `d-flex justify-content-center` is added to create a flex container for the images and center them horizontally.
- The `images.slice(i, i + 3)` is used to select a subset of three images starting from the current index `i`. This ensures that only three images are displayed side by side in each carousel item.
- The `img` elements are rendered with the class `d-inline-block mx-2` to display them inline and add horizontal margin between them.
- The `controls` prop of the `Carousel` component is set to `true` to display the previous and next controls for the slider.
- In the CSS code, the `carousel-item` class is given a fixed height (e.g., `200px`) to control the height of each carousel item. You can adjust this value as needed.
- The `carousel-item img` styles are updated to set the width to `auto` and height to `100%` to fit the images within the carousel item while maintaining their aspect ratio.

