MAKE THIS A LITTLE MORE OBVIOUS, PERHAPS PUT A BACKGROUND AROUND IT LIKE A PURPLE OVAL

To turn the "1000" into a countdown to 0 in the `DreamJobComponent.jsx`, you can use the `useState` and `useEffect` hooks in React. Here's how you can modify the code:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import './DreamJobComponent.css';

const DreamJobComponent = () => {
    const [remainingUsers, setRemainingUsers] = useState(1000);

    useEffect(() => {
        if (remainingUsers > 0) {
            const timer = setTimeout(() => {
                setRemainingUsers(prevCount => prevCount - 1);
            }, 1000);

            return () => clearTimeout(timer);
        }
    }, [remainingUsers]);

    return (
        <div className="dream-job-container">
            <h1>Land your <span className="highlight">dream job</span>.</h1>
            <h2>In Dubai.</h2>
            <p>Upload your CV once and let us do the work! Pineapply will automatically find relevant roles for you and automatically fill out job applications on your behalf.</p>
            <ul className="features-list">
                <li>Automated Job Tracking</li>
                <li>Optimize your LinkedIn Profile</li>
                <li>AI Resume Builder</li>
                <li>And much more!</li>
            </ul>
            <div className="buttons-container">
                <button className="btn add-to-chrome">Try it</button>
                <button className="btn learn-more">Learn More</button>
            </div>
            <h2>Currently accepting {remainingUsers} users only.</h2>
        </div>
    );
};

export default DreamJobComponent;
```

Explanation:
1. We import the `useState` and `useEffect` hooks from the 'react' module.
2. We declare a state variable called `remainingUsers` using the `useState` hook and initialize it with the value of 1000.
3. We use the `useEffect` hook to create a countdown effect. The effect runs whenever the `remainingUsers` state changes.
4. Inside the effect, we check if `remainingUsers` is greater than 0. If it is, we use `setTimeout` to schedule a state update after a 1-second delay (1000 milliseconds).
5. The state update is performed using the `setRemainingUsers` function, which decrements the `remainingUsers` count by 1 using the previous state value (`prevCount`).
6. We also provide a cleanup function inside the effect by returning a function that clears the timeout using `clearTimeout`. This ensures that the timer is cleared when the component unmounts or when the effect is re-run.
7. In the JSX, we replace the hardcoded "1000" with the `remainingUsers` state variable to display the current countdown value.

With these modifications, the "1000" will start counting down to 0 at a rate of one user per second. The countdown will stop when it reaches 0.

Note that this is a simulated countdown and doesn't actually track the number of users accepting the offer. If you want to integrate it with a real user registration system, you would need to update the `remainingUsers` state based on the actual number of users who have signed up.

Certainly! Here's the modified code to subtract 5 from the remaining users count every 3 hours:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import './DreamJobComponent.css';

const DreamJobComponent = () => {
    const [remainingUsers, setRemainingUsers] = useState(1000);

    useEffect(() => {
        const countdownInterval = setInterval(() => {
            setRemainingUsers(prevCount => {
                const newCount = prevCount - 5;
                return newCount >= 0 ? newCount : 0;
            });
        }, 3 * 60 * 60 * 1000); // 3 hours in milliseconds

        return () => clearInterval(countdownInterval);
    }, []);

    return (
        <div className="dream-job-container">
            <h1>Land your <span className="highlight">dream job</span>.</h1>
            <h2>In Dubai.</h2>
            <p>Upload your CV once and let us do the work! Pineapply will automatically find relevant roles for you and automatically fill out job applications on your behalf.</p>
            <ul className="features-list">
                <li>Automated Job Tracking</li>
                <li>Optimize your LinkedIn Profile</li>
                <li>AI Resume Builder</li>
                <li>And much more!</li>
            </ul>
            <div className="buttons-container">
                <button className="btn add-to-chrome">Try it</button>
                <button className="btn learn-more">Learn More</button>
            </div>
            <h2>Currently accepting {remainingUsers} users only.</h2>
        </div>
    );
};

export default DreamJobComponent;
```

Explanation:
1. We use the `useState` hook to initialize the `remainingUsers` state with a value of 1000.
2. Inside the `useEffect` hook, we set up an interval using `setInterval` that runs every 3 hours (3 * 60 * 60 * 1000 milliseconds).
3. Within the interval callback, we use the `setRemainingUsers` function to update the `remainingUsers` state.
4. We calculate the new count by subtracting 5 from the previous count (`prevCount - 5`).
5. We use a ternary operator to ensure that the new count doesn't go below 0. If the new count is greater than or equal to 0, we return the new count; otherwise, we return 0.
6. The interval will continue to run every 3 hours, subtracting 5 from the `remainingUsers` count each time, until the component is unmounted.
7. We provide a cleanup function inside the `useEffect` hook by returning a function that clears the interval using `clearInterval`. This ensures that the interval is cleared when the component unmounts.
8. In the JSX, we display the current value of `remainingUsers` to show the remaining user count.

With these modifications, the countdown will start at 1000 and subtract 5 every 3 hours until it reaches 0. The countdown will stop at 0 and won't go into negative values.

Please note that this countdown is simulated and doesn't persist across page refreshes or component remounts. If you want to persist the countdown state, you would need to store it in a more permanent storage mechanism such as local storage or a backend database.

