To achieve this, you can use a conditional statement to check the value of the gender variable and assign the appropriate string to the `instance_prompt` variable. Here's an example of how you can modify the code:

```javascript
let instance_prompt;

if (gender === 'man') {
  instance_prompt = "photo of a man";
} else if (gender === 'woman') {
  instance_prompt = "photo of a woman";
} else {
  // Handle any other cases or provide a default value if needed
  instance_prompt = "photo of a person";
}
```

In this example, we first declare a variable `instance_prompt` without assigning a value to it. Then, we use an `if...else` statement to check the value of the `gender` variable.

- If `gender` is equal to `'man'`, we assign the string `"photo of a man"` to `instance_prompt`.
- If `gender` is equal to `'woman'`, we assign the string `"photo of a woman"` to `instance_prompt`.
- If `gender` is neither `'man'` nor `'woman'`, we assign a default value `"photo of a person"` to `instance_prompt`. You can modify this default value as per your requirements.

After this conditional statement, the `instance_prompt` variable will hold the appropriate string based on the value of the `gender` variable.

You can then use the `instance_prompt` variable in your code as needed.

Alternatively, if you prefer a more concise syntax, you can use a ternary operator:

```javascript
const instance_prompt = gender === 'man' ? "photo of a man" : gender === 'woman' ? "photo of a woman" : "photo of a person";
```

This ternary operator achieves the same result as the `if...else` statement above, but in a more compact form. It checks the value of `gender` and assigns the corresponding string to `instance_prompt` based on the conditions.

Both approaches will work, and you can choose the one that best suits your coding style and preferences.

To access the `gender` state variable from your `Headshot.jsx` component in the `lightheadshot.js` file, you need to pass it as a prop from the parent component (`Headshot.jsx`) to the child component (`lightheadshot.js`).

