when i print imageurls it shows as empty array, why?

The reason why `imageUrls` is showing as an empty array when you log it after calling `fetchImageUrls()` is because the `fetchImageUrls` function is asynchronous, and the `console.log('Image URLs:', imageUrls);` statement is executed before the asynchronous operation completes.

In JavaScript, when an asynchronous operation is initiated, the code execution doesn't wait for the operation to complete. Instead, it continues to the next line of code, and the asynchronous operation runs in the background.

To ensure that the `imageUrls` array is logged after it has been populated with the image URLs, you need to move the `console.log` statement inside the `fetchImageUrls` function, specifically after the `imageUrls.push(...urls);` line.

Here's the updated code:

```javascript
import { getStorage, ref, listAll, getDownloadURL } from 'firebase/storage';

const dreamlookApiKey = 'dl-F3BFCB0668D04BE4BE9E5C1DDC2AB0A4';
const baseUrl = 'http://training-cheri.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com/vadim/';
const imageUrls = [];

const fetchImageUrls = async () => {
  const storage = getStorage();
  const folderRef = ref(storage, 'kareemy9000_gmail_com/');

  try {
    const listResult = await listAll(folderRef);
    const urlPromises = listResult.items.map((itemRef) => getDownloadURL(itemRef));
    const urls = await Promise.all(urlPromises);
    imageUrls.push(...urls);
    console.log('Image URLs:', imageUrls); // Log the imageUrls array here
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching KAREEMY9000 AI image URLs:', error);
  }
};

fetchImageUrls(); // Call the fetchImageUrls function
```

Now, when you run this code, the `console.log('Image URLs:', imageUrls);` statement will be executed after the `imageUrls` array has been populated with the image URLs fetched from Firebase Storage.

Alternatively, if you want to log the `imageUrls` array outside the `fetchImageUrls` function, you can use a `.then` callback or an `async/await` approach to ensure that the asynchronous operation has completed before logging the array.

Here's an example using the `.then` callback:

```javascript
import { getStorage, ref, listAll, getDownloadURL } from 'firebase/storage';

const dreamlookApiKey = 'dl-F3BFCB0668D04BE4BE9E5C1DDC2AB0A4';
const baseUrl = 'http://training-cheri.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com/vadim/';
const imageUrls = [];

const fetchImageUrls = async () => {
  const storage = getStorage();
  const folderRef = ref(storage, 'kareemy9000_gmail_com/');

  try {
    const listResult = await listAll(folderRef);
    const urlPromises = listResult.items.map((itemRef) => getDownloadURL(itemRef));
    const urls = await Promise.all(urlPromises);
    imageUrls.push(...urls);
    return imageUrls;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching KAREEMY9000 AI image URLs:', error);
  }
};

fetchImageUrls()
  .then((urls) => {
    console.log('Image URLs:', urls);
    // Continue with your code using the populated imageUrls array
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.error('Error:', error);
  });
```

In this example, the `fetchImageUrls` function returns the `imageUrls` array after it has been populated with the image URLs. Then, the `.then` callback is used to log the `imageUrls` array after the asynchronous operation has completed.

To access the `imageUrls` array containing the fetched image URLs later in your code, you can store it in a global variable or use a state management solution like React Context or Redux.

Here's an example of how you can store the `imageUrls` array in a global variable and access it later:

```javascript
import { getStorage, ref, listAll, getDownloadURL } from 'firebase/storage';

const dreamlookApiKey = 'dl-F3BFCB0668D04BE4BE9E5C1DDC2AB0A4';
const baseUrl = 'http://training-cheri.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com/vadim/';

// Declare a global variable to store the imageUrls array
let globalImageUrls = [];

const fetchImageUrls = async () => {
  const storage = getStorage();
  const folderRef = ref(storage, 'kareemy9000_gmail_com/');

  try {
    const listResult = await listAll(folderRef);
    const urlPromises = listResult.items.map((itemRef) => getDownloadURL(itemRef));
    const urls = await Promise.all(urlPromises);
    globalImageUrls = urls; // Store the fetched URLs in the global variable
    console.log('Image URLs:', globalImageUrls);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching KAREEMY9000 AI image URLs:', error);
  }
};

fetchImageUrls(); // Call the fetchImageUrls function

// Access the globalImageUrls array later in your code
console.log('Accessing globalImageUrls:', globalImageUrls);

// Example usage of globalImageUrls
function processImages() {
  globalImageUrls.forEach((url) => {
    // Do something with each image URL
    console.log('Processing image:', url);
  });
}

processImages();
```

In this example, we declare a global variable `globalImageUrls` outside the `fetchImageUrls` function. Inside the `fetchImageUrls` function, we assign the fetched image URLs to the `globalImageUrls` variable.

After calling `fetchImageUrls()`, you can access the `globalImageUrls` array anywhere in your code. The example code demonstrates logging the `globalImageUrls` array and using it in a `processImages` function.

However, using global variables is generally not recommended, especially in larger applications, as it can lead to naming conflicts and make the code harder to maintain and reason about.

A better approach would be to use a state management solution like React Context or Redux, which provides a centralized way to manage and access data across your application.

If you're using React, you can store the `imageUrls` array in the component state or a context provider, and then access it from other components as needed.

Here's a simple example using React Context:

```jsx
import React, { createContext, useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import { getStorage, ref, listAll, getDownloadURL } from 'firebase/storage';

const ImageUrlsContext = createContext();

const ImageUrlsProvider = ({ children }) => {
  const [imageUrls, setImageUrls] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchImageUrls = async () => {
      const storage = getStorage();
      const folderRef = ref(storage, 'kareemy9000_gmail_com/');

      try {
        const listResult = await listAll(folderRef);
        const urlPromises = listResult.items.map((itemRef) => getDownloadURL(itemRef));
        const urls = await Promise.all(urlPromises);
        setImageUrls(urls);
      } catch (error) {
        console.error('Error fetching KAREEMY9000 AI image URLs:', error);
      }
    };

    fetchImageUrls();
  }, []);

  return (
    <ImageUrlsContext.Provider value={imageUrls}>
      {children}
    </ImageUrlsContext.Provider>
  );
};

// Usage in a child component
const ChildComponent = () => {
  const imageUrls = React.useContext(ImageUrlsContext);

  return (
```

