To replace the `src` attribute of the `<img>` tag with the `imageUrls` array, you can use the `map` method to iterate over the array and create a new array of `<img>` elements with the corresponding URLs.

Here's an example of how you can do it in React:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

const ImageGallery = ({ imageUrls }) => {
  return (
    <div>
      {imageUrls.map((url, index) => (
        <img
          key={index}
          src={url}
          alt={`Face and neck not covered ${index}`}
          style={{ maxWidth: '200px', margin: '10px' }}
        />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};

export default ImageGallery;
```

In this example, the `ImageGallery` component takes an `imageUrls` prop, which is an array of image URLs. The component uses the `map` method to iterate over the `imageUrls` array and create an `<img>` element for each URL.

The `key` prop is required for React to efficiently update the rendered elements when the array changes. The `src` attribute is set to the corresponding URL from the `imageUrls` array, and the `alt` attribute is set to a descriptive text with the index of the image.

You can then use the `ImageGallery` component in your application like this:

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import ImageGallery from './ImageGallery';

const App = () => {
  const imageUrls = [
    'https://example.com/image1.jpg',
    'https://example.com/image2.jpg',
    'https://example.com/image3.jpg',
    // Add more image URLs here
  ];

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Image Gallery</h1>
      <ImageGallery imageUrls={imageUrls} />
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

In this example, the `imageUrls` array is defined in the `App` component, and it is passed as a prop to the `ImageGallery` component. The `ImageGallery` component will then render an `<img>` element for each URL in the `imageUrls` array.

Note that this example assumes you're using React. If you're not using React, you can achieve a similar result by creating the `<img>` elements dynamically using JavaScript and appending them to the desired container in the DOM.

If you have a single `imageRef` variable containing the URL of an image, you can replace the `src` attribute of the `<img>` tag with the value of that variable.

Here's an example:

```html
<img id="myImage" src="http://training-cheri.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com/56.jpg" alt="Face and neck not covered">

<script>
  const imageRef = 'https://example.com/new-image.jpg';
  const imageElement = document.getElementById('myImage');
  imageElement.src = imageRef;
</script>
```

In this example, we first have an `<img>` tag with the initial `src` attribute set to `"http://training-cheri.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com/56.jpg"`.

Then, in the `<script>` section, we define a variable `imageRef` and assign it the new image URL (`'https://example.com/new-image.jpg'`).

Next, we use `document.getElementById('myImage')` to get a reference to the `<img>` element with the ID `'myImage'`.

Finally, we update the `src` attribute of the `<img>` element by setting `imageElement.src = imageRef;`.

After running this code, the `<img>` tag will display the image from the new URL stored in the `imageRef` variable.

If you're using a JavaScript framework like React, you can achieve the same result by updating the `src` prop of the `<img>` component with the `imageRef` variable.

For example, in React:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

const ImageComponent = () => {
  const imageRef = 'https://example.com/new-image.jpg';

  return (
    <img src={imageRef} alt="Face and neck not covered" />
  );
};

export default ImageComponent;
```

In this example, the `imageRef` variable is defined within the `ImageComponent` functional component, and its value is used as the `src` prop of the `<img>` element.

