inside handlesubmit function, i need to display an error if the user hasnt selected a gender. Or if they uploaded

The code you provided already includes error handling for the gender selection and the number of images uploaded. Here's a breakdown of the relevant parts:

1. Gender error handling:
```javascript
if (gender === '') {
    setGenderError('Please select gender!');
    hasError = true;
} else {
    setGenderError('');
}
```
This block of code checks if the `gender` state is an empty string. If it is, it sets the `genderError` state with the error message "Please select gender!" and sets `hasError` to `true`. Otherwise, it clears the `genderError` state.

2. Image upload error handling:
```javascript
if (selectedFiles.length < 5) {
    setImageError('Please upload at least 5 images.');
    hasError = true;
} else if (selectedFiles.length > 20) {
    setImageError('Please don\'t upload more than 20 images.');
    hasError = true;
} else {
    setImageError('');
}
```
This block of code checks the length of the `selectedFiles` array. If the length is less than 5, it sets the `imageError` state with the error message "Please upload at least 5 images." and sets `hasError` to `true`. If the length is greater than 20, it sets the `imageError` state with the error message "Please don't upload more than 20 images." and sets `hasError` to `true`. Otherwise, it clears the `imageError` state.

3. Error display:
The error messages for gender and image upload are displayed using the following code:

```jsx
{genderError && <Alert variant="danger" className="mt-2">{genderError}</Alert>}
{imageError && <Alert variant="danger" className="mt-2">{imageError}</Alert>}
```
These lines of code conditionally render an `Alert` component from the `react-bootstrap` library if the respective error state (`genderError` or `imageError`) is truthy (i.e., not an empty string). The `Alert` component displays the error message in a visually distinct way.

4. Form submission prevention:
The code also includes a check to prevent form submission if there are any errors:

```javascript
if (hasError) {
    return;
}
```
If `hasError` is `true`, the function returns early, preventing further execution and form submission.

So, the code already handles the scenarios you mentioned: displaying an error if the user hasn't selected a gender or if they haven't uploaded the correct number of images (between 5 and 20). The error messages are displayed using the `Alert` components from `react-bootstrap`.

You're right, the current implementation only displays one error at a time. To display multiple errors simultaneously, you can modify the code to store all the errors in an array and then render them together.

Here's how you can modify the code:

1. Create a new state variable to store the errors:

```javascript
const [errors, setErrors] = useState([]);
```

2. Update the error handling logic in the `handleSubmit` function:

```javascript
const handleSubmit = async (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    const errors = [];

    if (checkboxes.some(checkbox => !checkbox)) {
        errors.push('You must check all the boxes!');
    }

    if (gender === '') {
        errors.push('Please select gender!');
    }

    if (selectedFiles.length < 5) {
        errors.push('Please upload at least 5 images.');
    } else if (selectedFiles.length > 20) {
        errors.push('Please don\'t upload more than 20 images.');
    }

    if (errors.length > 0) {
        setErrors(errors);
        return;
    }

    setErrors([]);
    // Rest of the code...
};
```

In this updated code, we create an empty `errors` array at the beginning of the `handleSubmit` function. Then, instead of setting individual error states (`checkboxError`, `genderError`, `imageError`), we push the error messages to the `errors` array.

If the `errors` array has any elements after all the checks, we set the `errors` state with the array of error messages and return early to prevent form submission.

3. Render the errors:

```jsx
{errors.length > 0 && (
    <div>
        {errors.map((error, index) => (
            <Alert key={index} variant="danger" className="mt-2">
                {error}
            </Alert>
        ))}
    </div>
)}
```

This code block renders an `Alert` component for each error message in the `errors` array. You can place this code block wherever you want to display the errors in your component.

With these changes, your component will display all the errors simultaneously if there are multiple issues with the form data.

You can place the error rendering code block anywhere in your component's JSX where you want to display the errors. A common practice is to place it near the top of the component, right after the opening `<div>` or `<Container>` element.

Here's an example of where you could place it in your existing code:

```jsx
return (
    <>
        <Navbar />
        <div className="page-container">
            <Container className="headshot-container d-flex align-items-center justify-content-center text-center">
                {/* Render errors here */}
                {errors.length > 0 && (
                    <div>
                        {errors.map((error, index) => (
                            <Alert key={index} variant="danger" className="mt-2">
                                {error}
                            </Alert>
                        ))}
                    </div>
                )}

                <div className="text-center mb-5">
                    {/* ... */}
                </div>

                {/* Rest of your component */}
            </Container>
        </div>
    </>
);
```

By placing the error rendering code block inside the `<Container>` element, the errors will be displayed within the main content area of your component.

Alternatively, you could also render the errors outside the `<Container>` element, before or after it, depending on your preference and layout requirements.

```jsx
return (
    <>
        <Navbar />
        <div className="page-container">
            {/* Render errors here */}
            {errors.length > 0 && (
                <div>
                    {errors.map((error, index) => (
                        <Alert key={index} variant="danger" className="mt-2">
                            {error}
                        </Alert>
                    ))}
                </div>
            )}

            <Container className="headshot-container d-flex align-items-center justify-content-center text-center">
                {/* ... */}
            </Container>
        </div>
    </>
);
```

In this case, the errors will be displayed outside the main content area, but still within the `page-container` div.

The choice of where to place the error rendering code block depends on your design and layout preferences, as well as the desired positioning of the error messages relative to the rest of the component's content.

import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import { useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom';
import { auth, googleAuthProvider } from '../../firebaseauth.js';
import GoogleButton from 'react-google-button';
import { signInWithPopup, onAuthStateChanged, sendSignInLinkToEmail } from 'firebase/auth';
import { getFirestore, doc, runTransaction } from 'firebase/firestore';
import Navbar from &quot;../../components/Navbar/Navbar.jsx&quot;;
import Footer from &quot;../../components/Footer/Footer.jsx&quot;;
import { Stack, Button, Input } from &quot;@mui/joy&quot;;
import './Login.scss';

const Loginpage = () =&gt; {
    const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
    const [error, setError] = useState(null);
    const [email, setEmail] = useState('');
    const [message, setMessage] = useState('');
    const navigate = useNavigate();

    useEffect(() =&gt; {
        const unsubscribe = onAuthStateChanged(auth, user =&gt; {
            if (user) {
                navigate('/');
            }
        });
        return unsubscribe;
    }, [navigate]);

    const handleSignWithGoogle = async () =&gt; {
        // ... (existing code for Google sign-in)
    };

    const handleSendMagicLink = async () =&gt; {
        setLoading(true);
        setError(null);
        setMessage('');
        try {
            const actionCodeSettings = {
                url: 'https://www.pineapply.ai/landing', // Replace with your desired URL
                handleCodeInApp: true,
            };
            await sendSignInLinkToEmail(auth, email, actionCodeSettings);
            window.localStorage.setItem('emailForSignIn', email);
            setMessage('Magic link sent! Please check your email.');
        } catch (error) {
            setError(error.message);
        }
        setLoading(false);
    };

    const handleEmailChange = (e) =&gt; {
        setEmail(e.target.value);
    };

    return (
        &lt;&gt;
            {/* UI components */}
            &lt;Stack sx={{ minHeight: '100vh' }}&gt;
                &lt;Navbar /&gt;
                &lt;div className=&quot;login-card&quot;&gt;
                    &lt;GoogleButton onClick={handleSignWithGoogle} disabled={loading} /&gt;
                    &lt;Input
                        placeholder=&quot;Email&quot;
                        type=&quot;email&quot;
                        value={email}
                        onChange={handleEmailChange}
                        disabled={loading}
                        sx={{ marginTop: '16px' }}
                    /&gt;
                    &lt;Button onClick={handleSendMagicLink} disabled={loading} sx={{ marginTop: '16px' }}&gt;
                        Send Magic Link
                    &lt;/Button&gt;
                    {message &amp;&amp; &lt;p className=&quot;message&quot;&gt;{message}&lt;/p&gt;}
                    {error &amp;&amp; &lt;p className=&quot;error-message&quot;&gt;{error}&lt;/p&gt;}
                &lt;/div&gt;
            &lt;/Stack&gt;
            &lt;Footer /&gt;
        &lt;/&gt;
    );
};

export default Loginpage; 

Stylize the text, why is the sign in with google not working?

The issue with the Google sign-in not working could be due to a few reasons:

1. **Missing Google Authentication Provider Setup**

In your code, you're importing `googleAuthProvider` from `firebaseauth.js`, but you're not using it anywhere in the `handleSignWithGoogle` function. You need to set up the Google Authentication Provider and use it with the `signInWithPopup` function from the Firebase Authentication SDK.

Here's how you can update the `handleSignWithGoogle` function:

```jsx
const handleSignWithGoogle = async () => {
    try {
        setLoading(true);
        const result = await signInWithPopup(auth, googleAuthProvider);
        // Handle the result as needed
        console.log(result.user);
    } catch (error) {
        setError(error.message);
    } finally {
        setLoading(false);
    }
};
```

Make sure that you've properly set up the `googleAuthProvider` in your `firebaseauth.js` file. You can refer to the Firebase documentation for more details: https://firebase.google.com/docs/auth/web/google-signin

