The reason why the "Magic link sent! Please check your email." message moves when you scroll is because it's positioned using `position: fixed`. This CSS property makes an element fixed relative to the viewport, so it stays in the same place even when the page is scrolled.

To prevent the message from moving when scrolling, you can use `position: absolute` instead of `position: fixed`. This will make the message positioned relative to its nearest positioned ancestor (e.g., the `<body>` element or a parent container with `position: relative`).

Here's how you can update the CSS for the `magic-link-message` class:

```css
.magic-link-message {
    position: absolute;
    top: 50%;
    left: 50%;
    transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
    background-color: #fff;
    padding: 20px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.15);
    z-index: 1000;
    text-align: center;
}
```

The only change is replacing `position: fixed` with `position: absolute`.

With this change, the message container will be positioned relative to its nearest positioned ancestor, and it will move along with the page content when scrolling.

However, keep in mind that if the message container is rendered outside of the viewport (e.g., if the page is scrolled down), it may not be visible. In that case, you might need to adjust the positioning or add additional logic to ensure the message is always visible within the viewport.

Alternatively, if you want the message to stay fixed in the center of the viewport even when scrolling, you can keep `position: fixed` and add some additional CSS to prevent the message from moving when scrolling:

```css
.magic-link-message {
    position: fixed;
    top: 50%;
    left: 50%;
    transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
    background-color: #fff;
    padding: 20px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.15);
    z-index: 1000;
    text-align: center;
    pointer-events: none; /* Prevent the message from capturing mouse events */
}
```

The `pointer-events: none` property will prevent the message container from capturing mouse events, which can cause the page to scroll when interacting with the message.

Choose the approach that best suits your requirements and desired behavior for the message container.

