To change the lazy import to a normal import, you can modify the code as follows:

```jsx
import HeadshotSuccess from './headshotsuccess.jsx';
```

The `lazy` function is used in React to enable code-splitting and lazy-loading of components. It allows you to load components asynchronously when they are needed, rather than bundling the entire application upfront.

When using a normal import, the component will be bundled and loaded with the rest of the application code. This means that the initial bundle size may be larger, but the component will be available immediately without the need for additional network requests.

Here's an example of how you might use the `HeadshotSuccess` component after importing it normally:

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import HeadshotSuccess from './headshotsuccess.jsx';

const App = () => {
  const [isSubmitSuccessful, setIsSubmitSuccessful] = React.useState(false);

  const handleSubmit = () => {
    // Perform submit logic
    setIsSubmitSuccessful(true);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      {/* ... */}
      {isSubmitSuccessful && <HeadshotSuccess />}
      {/* ... */}
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

In this example, the `HeadshotSuccess` component is imported directly and rendered conditionally based on the `isSubmitSuccessful` state.

Keep in mind that using a normal import means the component will be included in the initial bundle, which may increase the bundle size and potentially impact the initial load time of your application. If the `HeadshotSuccess` component is large or not needed immediately, it might be better to keep the lazy import to improve the initial load performance.

