if a user is not logged in and tries to access /dashboard we must redirect him to the /login page. Please give me JUST THE RELEVANT CODE LINES

The relevant code lines for redirecting the user to the `/login` page if they are not logged in and try to access the `/dashboard` route are:

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    if (loading) return;
    if (!user) navigate("/login");

    // ...
}, [user, loading, navigate]);
```

In this code snippet, the `useEffect` hook is used to check if the user is logged in or not. If the `loading` state is `true`, it means that the authentication state is still being loaded, so it returns without doing anything.

If the `user` is falsy (i.e., not logged in), the `navigate` function from `react-router-dom` is called with the argument `/login`, which redirects the user to the `/login` page.

The `useEffect` hook is set to run whenever the `user`, `loading`, or `navigate` values change, ensuring that the check is performed whenever the authentication state or the navigation function changes.

    useEffect(() =&gt; {
        if (loading) return;
        if (!user) navigate(&quot;/login&quot;);

        const fetchUserData = async () =&gt; {
            try {
                const userDocRef = doc(db, &quot;Users&quot;, user.uid);
                const userDoc = await getDoc(userDocRef);
                if (userDoc.exists()) {
                    const userData = userDoc.data();
                    setStats(prevStats =&gt; ({
                        ...prevStats,
                        creditsLeft: userData.Credits || 0,
                        totalApplications: userData.totalApplications || 0,
                        successRate: userData.successRate || 0
                    }));
                    setResume(userData.resume);
                    setPreferredJobTitles(userData.jobTitles || []);
                    setBlockedEmployers(userData.blocked || []);
                } else {
                    console.log(&quot;No such document!&quot;);
                }
            } catch (error) {
                console.error(&quot;Error fetching user data:&quot;, error);
            }
        };

        fetchUserData();
    }, [user, loading, navigate]);

I ALREADY HAVE THIS BUT IF THE USER TYPES &quot;/dashboard&quot; in the URL it will take him to an error page

To handle the case where the user types "/dashboard" in the URL directly and they are not logged in, you can wrap the `Dashboard` component with a `PrivateRoute` component that checks if the user is authenticated before rendering the `Dashboard` component. If the user is not authenticated, it can redirect them to the login page.

Here's an example of how you can create a `PrivateRoute` component:

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import { Navigate, useLocation } from 'react-router-dom';
import { useAuthState } from 'react-firebase-hooks/auth';
import { auth } from './firebaseauth';

const PrivateRoute = ({ children }) => {
    const [user, loading] = useAuthState(auth);
    const location = useLocation();

    if (loading) {
        return <div>Loading...</div>;
    }

    if (!user) {
        return <Navigate to="/login" state={{ from: location }} replace />;
    }

    return children;
};

export default PrivateRoute;
```

In this `PrivateRoute` component:

1. We import the necessary dependencies, including `useAuthState` from `react-firebase-hooks/auth` and `auth` from `firebaseauth.js`.
2. We use the `useAuthState` hook to get the current user and loading state.
3. If the loading state is true, we render a "Loading..." message.
4. If the user is not authenticated (`!user`), we use the `Navigate` component from `react-router-dom` to redirect the user to the `/login` page. We also pass the current location (`location`) as state to the `/login` page, so that we can redirect the user back to the intended page after successful login.
5. If the user is authenticated, we render the children components (in this case, the `Dashboard` component).

Now, you can wrap the `Dashboard` component with the `PrivateRoute` component in your routing configuration:

```jsx
import { BrowserRouter as Router, Routes, Route } from 'react-router-dom';
import Dashboard from './pages/Dashboard/Dashboard';
import Login from './pages/Login';
import PrivateRoute from './PrivateRoute';

const App = () => {
    return (
        <Router>
            <Routes>
                <Route path="/login" element={<Login />} />
                <Route
                    path="/dashboard"
                    element={
                        <PrivateRoute>
                            <Dashboard />
                        </PrivateRoute>
                    }
                />
                {/* Add other routes here */}
            </Routes>
        </Router>
    );
};

export default App;
```

With this setup, if the user tries to access the `/dashboard` route directly without being authenticated, they will be redirected to the `/login` page. After successful login, they will be redirected back to the `/dashboard` route.

