You're correct. The URLs returned by the `scrapeWorkableForListings` function should all start with `https://jobs.workable.com/` before the specific job listing URL path.

To ensure this, you can modify the `page.evaluate` function that extracts the job URLs. Instead of returning the `href` attribute directly, you can construct the full URL by concatenating the base URL (`https://jobs.workable.com/`) with the relative path.

Here's the updated code:

```javascript
const jobUrls = await page.evaluate(() => {
    const listings = document.querySelectorAll("[data-ui='job-item']");
    return Array.from(listings).map(job => {
        const relativeUrl = job.querySelector("h2 a").getAttribute("href");
        return `https://jobs.workable.com/${relativeUrl}`;
    });
});
```

In this updated code, we're using the `map` function to iterate over each job listing element. For each listing, we extract the relative URL path using `job.querySelector("h2 a").getAttribute("href")`, and then we construct the full URL by concatenating `https://jobs.workable.com/` with the relative path.

With this change, the `jobUrls` array will contain the complete URLs starting with `https://jobs.workable.com/` followed by the specific job listing URL path.

To look for the button with the provided class and data-ui attribute, and click it if it exists, you can add the following code before the `page.evaluate` function that extracts the job URLs:

```javascript
try {
    const declineButton = await page.$('button[data-ui="cookie-consent-decline"]');
    if (declineButton) {
        console.log('Decline cookies button found, clicking...');
        await declineButton.click();
        await page.waitForNavigation();
    } else {
        console.log('Decline cookies button not found');
    }
} catch (error) {
    console.error('Error handling decline cookies button:', error);
}
```

Here's what this code does:

1. It uses `page.$` to find the button element with the selector `'button[data-ui="cookie-consent-decline"]'`. This selector looks for a `button` element with the `data-ui` attribute set to `"cookie-consent-decline"`.
2. If the button is found (`declineButton` is not `null`), it logs a message and clicks the button using `await declineButton.click()`.
3. After clicking the button, it waits for the page navigation to complete using `await page.waitForNavigation()`. This is necessary because clicking the "Decline all" button might navigate to a different page or reload the current page.
4. If the button is not found, it logs a message indicating that the button was not found.
5. If any error occurs during this process, it catches the error and logs an error message.

With this code added before the `page.evaluate` function, it will attempt to find and click the "Decline all" button for cookie consent. If the button is not found or an error occurs, it will log the appropriate message and continue with the scraping process.

