Certainly! You can check if the entered email exists in an array of paying users before allowing them to click the "Submit" button. Here's how you can modify the code to achieve that:

```jsx
const [email, setEmail] = useState('');
const [emailError, setEmailError] = useState('');
const [isPayingUser, setIsPayingUser] = useState(false);

// Array of paying user emails
const payingUserEmails = ['user1@example.com', 'user2@example.com', 'user3@example.com'];

// ... (rest of the code)

const validateEmail = (email) => {
    // Simple email validation regex pattern
    const emailPattern = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/;
    return emailPattern.test(email);
};

const handleEmailChange = (e) => {
    const newEmail = e.target.value;
    setEmail(newEmail);

    if (newEmail.trim() === '') {
        setEmailError('');
        setIsPayingUser(false);
    } else if (!validateEmail(newEmail)) {
        setEmailError('E-mail not valid');
        setIsPayingUser(false);
    } else if (!payingUserEmails.includes(newEmail)) {
        setEmailError('E-mail not found in paying users');
        setIsPayingUser(false);
    } else {
        setEmailError('');
        setIsPayingUser(true);
    }
};

// ... (rest of the code)

{/* Email form */}
<Card className="email-card my-4" style={{ width: '100%', maxWidth: '600px', backgroundColor: '#f8f9fa' }}>
    <Card.Body>
        <Card.Title className="mb-4" style={{ color: 'black' }}>Enter Your Email</Card.Title>
        <Form.Group controlId="emailInput">
            <Form.Control
                type="email"
                placeholder="Enter your email"
                value={email}
                onChange={handleEmailChange}
                style={{ borderRadius: '25px', padding: '10px 20px', color: 'black' }}
            />
            {emailError && (
                <Form.Text style={{ color: 'red', marginTop: '8px' }}>{emailError}</Form.Text>
            )}
        </Form.Group>
    </Card.Body>
</Card>

{/* "Submit" button */}
<Button
    variant="primary"
    onClick={handleSubmit}
    disabled={selectedFiles.length === 0 || selectedFiles.length > 20 || loading || !email || emailError || !isPayingUser}
    className="mt-2"
    style={{ backgroundColor: '#007bff', borderColor: '#007bff', borderRadius: '25px', padding: '10px 30px', color: 'black' }}
>
    {loading ? 'Processing...' : 'Submit'}
</Button>
```

The changes made:
- Added a new state variable `isPayingUser` to keep track of whether the entered email belongs to a paying user.
- Defined an array `payingUserEmails` that contains the emails of paying users.
- Updated the `handleEmailChange` function to check if the entered email exists in the `payingUserEmails` array. If the email is not found, it sets the `emailError` state to "E-mail not found in paying users" and sets `isPayingUser` to `false`. If the email is found, it clears the `emailError` state and sets `isPayingUser` to `true`.
- Updated the `disabled` prop of the "Submit" button to include the condition `!isPayingUser` to disable the button if the entered email does not belong to a paying user.

Now, when a user enters an email, it will be checked against the `payingUserEmails` array. If the email is not found in the array, an error message "E-mail not found in paying users" will be displayed, and the "Submit" button will be disabled. If the email is found in the array, the error message will be cleared, and the "Submit" button will be enabled.

