Certainly! If `lightheadshot.js` is a JavaScript file within your project that will call an external API, you can directly import the necessary functions from `lightheadshot.js` into your `headshot.jsx` file and pass the uploaded images to those functions.

Here's an example of how you can modify the `handleSubmit` function in `headshot.jsx` to pass the uploaded images to `lightheadshot.js`:

```jsx
import { processImages } from './lightheadshot.js';

// ...

const handleSubmit = async () => {
    if (selectedFiles.length === 0) {
        setErrorMessage('Please select at least one image.');
        return;
    }

    if (selectedFiles.length > 15) {
        setErrorMessage('You can upload a maximum of 15 images.');
        return;
    }

    setLoading(true);

    try {
        // Pass the selected files to the processImages function in lightheadshot.js
        await processImages(selectedFiles);

        // Reset form after successful submission
        setSelectedFiles([]);
        setEmail('');
        setGender('man');
        setIsPayingUser(false);
        // Redirect to the success page or show a success message
        // Example: history.push('/success');
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('Error processing images:', error);
        // Handle the error case
    }

    setLoading(false);
};
```

In this updated code:

1. Import the `processImages` function from `lightheadshot.js` at the top of your `headshot.jsx` file.

2. Inside the `handleSubmit` function, after the validation checks, call the `processImages` function and pass the `selectedFiles` as an argument.

3. The `processImages` function in `lightheadshot.js` will receive the uploaded images and can then make the necessary API calls to the external service.

4. If the `processImages` function completes successfully, the form is reset by clearing the `selectedFiles`, `email`, `gender`, and `isPayingUser` states.

5. After a successful submission, you can choose to redirect the user to a success page or show a success message, similar to the previous example.

6. If an error occurs during the image processing, it is caught in the `catch` block, and you can handle the error case accordingly.

Now, in your `lightheadshot.js` file, you can define the `processImages` function that receives the uploaded images and makes the necessary API calls to the external service. Here's an example:

```javascript
// lightheadshot.js

export const processImages = async (images) => {
    try {
        // Make API calls to the external service using the provided images
        // Example: const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/process-images', { ... });
        // Handle the API response and perform any necessary actions
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('Error processing images:', error);
        throw error;
    }
};
```

In this example, the `processImages` function receives the `images` parameter, which contains the uploaded images. Inside the function, you can make the necessary API calls to the external service using the provided images. Handle the API response and perform any required actions based on the response.

Make sure to replace `'https://api.example.com/process-images'` with the actual URL of the external API endpoint you are using.

By structuring your code this way, you can keep the image processing logic separate in `lightheadshot.js` and simply import and call the necessary functions in your `headshot.jsx` file.

