To display green checkmarks instead of bullet points in the checklist, you can use Unicode characters or custom CSS styles. Here are two approaches:

1. Using Unicode characters:

```jsx
<Card.Text>
  <span> Clear face and facial features.</span>
  <br />
  <span> Face and neck should not be covered.</span>
</Card.Text>
```

In this approach, the green checkmark is represented by the Unicode character "" (U+2705). The `<br />` tag is used to add a line break between the list items.

2. Using custom CSS styles:

```jsx
<Card.Text>
  <ul className="checklist">
    <li>Clear face and facial features.</li>
    <li>Face and neck should not be covered.</li>
  </ul>
</Card.Text>
```

```css
.checklist {
  list-style-type: none;
  padding-left: 20px;
}

.checklist li::before {
  content: "";
  color: green;
  font-weight: bold;
  display: inline-block;
  width: 1em;
  margin-left: -1em;
}
```

In this approach, a custom CSS class `checklist` is added to the `<ul>` element. The `list-style-type` property is set to `none` to remove the default bullet points.

The `::before` pseudo-element is used to insert the green checkmark symbol () before each list item. The `content` property sets the checkmark character, and the `color` property sets its color to green. The `font-weight` property makes the checkmark bold.

The `display`, `width`, and `margin-left` properties are used to position the checkmark correctly before each list item.

Choose the approach that best fits your project's styling requirements. If you prefer a simple solution without additional CSS, the first approach using Unicode characters would be sufficient. If you need more control over the styling or want to maintain consistency with your project's CSS, the second approach with custom CSS styles would be more suitable.

