  // ...

  return (
    <>
      <Navbar />
      <Container className="headshot-container d-flex align-items-center justify-content-center text-center" style={{ minHeight: '100vh', flexDirection: 'column' }}>
        {/* ... */}
        <Form.Group controlId="genderSelect" className="mb-3" style={{ width: 'auto', display: 'inline-block' }}>
          <Form.Label>Select Your Gender</Form.Label>
          <Form.Select value={gender} onChange={(e) => setGender(e.target.value)} style={{ width: 'auto' }}>
            <option value="man">Man</option>
            <option value="woman">Woman</option>
          </Form.Select>
        </Form.Group>
        {/* ... */}
      </Container>
      <Footer />
    </>
  );
}

module.exports = Headshot;
```

In this updated code:
- The `import` statements for React, React hooks, React Bootstrap components, Navbar, Footer, and axios are changed to use the `require` syntax.
- The `import` statement for the `headshot.scss` file is changed to use `require('./headshot.scss')`.
- The AWS SDK import is changed to `const AWS = require('aws-sdk')`.
- The `export default Headshot;` statement at the end of the component is changed to `module.exports = Headshot;`.

Please note that when using the `require` syntax, you need to make sure that your project is set up to work with CommonJS modules instead of ES modules. If you are using a build tool like webpack or Babel, you may need to configure them accordingly to handle CommonJS modules.

Also, keep in mind that using `require` instead of `import` may affect the way your code is bundled and loaded in the browser. Make sure to test your application thoroughly after making this change to ensure everything works as expected.

