I apologize for the confusion. It seems like the issue might be related to the `ProtectedRoute` component. If the `ProtectedRoute` component is redirecting to the `/login` route when the user is not authenticated, it could cause the behavior you're experiencing.

To resolve this, you can modify the `ProtectedRoute` component to redirect to the `/home` route instead of the `/login` route when the user is not authenticated. Here's an example of how you can update the `ProtectedRoute` component:

```jsx
// ProtectedRoute.jsx
import React from 'react';
import { Navigate } from 'react-router-dom';
import { useAuthState } from 'react-firebase-hooks/auth';
import { auth } from '../../firebaseauth.js';

const ProtectedRoute = ({ children }) => {
  const [user, loading] = useAuthState(auth);

  if (loading) {
    return <div>Loading...</div>;
  }

  if (!user) {
    return <Navigate to="/home" replace />; // Redirect to /home if user is not authenticated
  }

  return children;
};

export default ProtectedRoute;
```

In this updated `ProtectedRoute` component:

1. If the user is not authenticated (`!user`), the component redirects to the `/home` route instead of the `/login` route.

2. The `replace` prop is added to the `Navigate` component to replace the current entry in the history stack, preventing the user from going back to the protected route.

Make sure to update the `ProtectedRoute` component in your codebase with these changes.

With this modification, when a user visits the site for the first time and is not authenticated, they will be redirected to the `/home` route instead of the `/login` route.

If the issue persists, please double-check that you have updated the `ProtectedRoute` component correctly and that you have the `Home` component properly defined in the `./pages/Home/Home.jsx` file.

