Here are a few ways to make that content responsive and prevent overlapping:

1. Wrap it in a flexbox:

```jsx
<div className="flex-container">
  <div className="text-container">
    // content 
  </div>
</div>
```

```css
.flex-container {
  display: flex; 
  flex-wrap: wrap;
}
```

2. Use CSS Grid:

```css 
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  grid-gap: 20px;
}
```

3. Add media queries:

```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .text-container { 
    max-width: 100%;
  }
}
```

4. Limit the width:

```css
.text-container {
  max-width: 800px;
  margin: 0 auto;
}
```

5. Use responsive text sizes:

```css  
h1 {
  font-size: 2rem;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  h1 {
    font-size: 3rem;
  }
}
```

This will prevent the text from overflowing on smaller screens. Let me know if you need any other tips!

Here are a few ways to make all text on a page responsive:

1. Use rem or em units for font-sizes instead of pixels. This will allow text to scale up and down based on the root font-size.

2. Apply a max-width to sections of text or the entire content area:

```css
.content {
  max-width: 800px;
  margin: 0 auto;
}
```

3. Use responsive font-size and line-height:

```css
body {
  font-size: 1rem; 
  line-height: 1.5;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  body {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
  }
} 
```

4. Limit paragraph widths: 

```css
p {
  max-width: 75ch; /* about 75 characters wide */
}
```

5. Use utilities like Bootstrap's `.text-break` to break words:

```html
<p class="text-break">...</p> 
```

6. Set text containers to flexbox or CSS grids so they take up available space.

7. Use utilities like `.small`, `.large` to reduce sizes on small screens.

The key is using relative units, max-widths, and breakpoints to fluidly adapt text. Test on different device sizes to make sure it reflows nicely. Let me know if you have any other questions!

Here are a few ways to make that Typography component with maxWidth responsive:

1. Use a media query to reduce maxWidth on smaller screens:

```css
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .MuiTypography-root {
    max-width: 90%;
  }
}
```

2. Remove maxWidth and add word-break:

```css
.MuiTypography-root {
  word-break: break-word;
}
```

3. Set width in rem units instead of pixels:

```css
.MuiTypography-root {
  width: 60rem; 
}
```

4. Wrap it in a flex container:

```jsx
<div className="flex-container">
  <Typography>...</Typography>
</div>
```

```css
.flex-container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
}
```

5. Use the sx prop to make it responsive:

```jsx
<Typography 
  sx={{ 
    maxWidth: { xs: '90%', sm: '800px' }
  }}
>
```

This will apply different maxWidths based on screen size.

Let me know if you need any other tips! Responsive typography takes some thoughtful styling but these examples should help get you started.

