To contain the Carousel images in a slider with a fixed width, you can do the following:

1. Wrap the Carousel in a div with a max-width:

```jsx
<div className="carousel-container">
  <Carousel>
    // items 
  </Carousel>
</div>
```

```css
.carousel-container {
  max-width: 800px;
  margin: 0 auto; 
}
```

2. Set fixed heights/widths on the images:

```css
.carousel img {
  height: 400px;
  width: auto;
  max-width: 100%;
}
```

3. Override the Carousel styles:

```css
.carousel .carousel-inner {
  height: 400px; 
}

.carousel-item {
  max-width: 250px; // item width  
}
```

4. Adjust number of visible slides:

```jsx
<Carousel slidesToShow={3}>
```

5. Add proper spacing with CSS:

```css
.carousel-item {
  margin-right: 20px; 
}

.carousel-item:last-child {
  margin-right: 0;
}
```

This will set up a responsive slider with fixed item widths and spacing. Let me know if you need any help tweaking the styles further!

Here is one way to make the Carousel responsive as a slider:

```jsx
// Carousel component

<Carousel 
  className="image-slider"
  controls={true}
  indicators={false}
  interval={3000}
>
  {images.map(img => (
    <Carousel.Item>
      <img src={img.src} />
    </Carousel.Item>
  ))}
</Carousel>
```

```css
/* Slider styles */

.image-slider {
  max-width: 800px;
  margin: 0 auto;
}

.carousel-inner {
  height: 500px; // fixed height
} 

.carousel-item {
  max-width: 100%; // full width slides
  height: 500px; 
}

.carousel-item img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: cover; 
}

/* Responsive adjustments */

@media (max-width: 768px) {

  .image-slider,
  .carousel-inner,
  .carousel-item {
    height: 300px; 
  }

}
```

The key points:

- Fixed height on carousel and items
- 100% width on items for full bleed 
- object-fit: cover on images to scale nicely
- Media queries to reduce height on smaller screens

Let me know if you would like me to explain any part of this in more detail!

Here is some example code to create a sticky footer that stays at the bottom of the page:

```jsx
// App.js

return (
  <div className="app">
    <header>...</header>

    <main className="content">
      {/* Page content */}
    </main>

    <footer className="footer">
      {/* Footer content */} 
    </footer>
  </div>
)
```

```css
/* CSS */

.app {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  min-height: 100vh; 
}

.content {
  flex: 1;
}

.footer {
  position: absolute;
  bottom: 0;
  width: 100%;
  /* Footer styles */
}
```

The key points:

- Use flexbox on a wrapper element like `.app` 
- Give `.content` a flex-grow value to fill space
- Absolutely position footer to the bottom 
- Make sure `.app` has min-height: 100vh

This will cause the `.content` to take up remaining space, and keep the footer stuck to the bottom.

Some other tips:

- Clear floats in content to avoid layout issues 
- Set background colors on `.app`, `.content`, and `.footer`
- Use media queries to adjust positioning for mobile

