const useStyles = makeStyles((theme) => ({
    appTheme: {
        color: theme.palette.appTheme.main, // Replace 'appTheme' with the appropriate color in your theme
    },
}));

// ...

const PrivacyPolicy = () => {
    const classes = useStyles();

    return (
        <Card.Text>
            <Typography variant="h6" className={classes.appTheme}>
                Good examples of uploaded images:
            </Typography>
            <br />

            <div style={{ display: 'flex', flexWrap: 'wrap', justifyContent: 'center' }}>
                {/* ... */}
            </div>
        </Card.Text>
    );
};
```

In this updated code:

1. We import the `Typography` component from the `@material-ui/core` library.
2. We also import the `makeStyles` function from `@material-ui/core/styles` to create a custom CSS class for the 'appTheme' color.
3. Inside the `useStyles` hook, we define a new class called `appTheme` and set its color to `theme.palette.appTheme.main`. You'll need to replace 'appTheme' with the appropriate color in your theme object.
4. In the `PrivacyPolicy` component, we call the `useStyles` hook to get access to the custom CSS classes.
5. We replace the `<b>` element with a `<Typography>` component and apply the `appTheme` class to it.

Now, the heading "Good examples of uploaded images:" will be rendered as a `Typography` component with the color specified by the 'appTheme' color in your Material-UI theme.

Note: Make sure you have set up the Material-UI theme correctly in your project, and replace 'appTheme' with the appropriate color name in your theme object.

