REPLACE THE URLS IN IMAGEURLS WITH A FIREBASE STORAGE FOLDER

To replace the URLs in the `imageUrls` array with images from a Firebase Storage folder, you can use the `getDownloadURL` function from the `firebase/storage` module. Here's an example of how you can modify the code:

```javascript
import { getStorage, ref, listAll, getDownloadURL } from 'firebase/storage';

const dreamlookApiKey = 'dl-F3BFCB0668D04BE4BE9E5C1DDC2AB0A4';
const baseUrl = 'http://training-cheri.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com/vadim/';
const imageUrls = []; // This array will be populated with image URLs from Firebase Storage

// Replace 'your-firebase-storage-bucket' with the name of your Firebase Storage bucket
const storage = getStorage('your-firebase-storage-bucket');
const folderRef = ref(storage, 'path/to/your/folder');

// Fetch image URLs from the specified folder
listAll(folderRef)
  .then((res) => {
    const promises = res.items.map((itemRef) => getDownloadURL(itemRef));
    return Promise.all(promises);
  })
  .then((urls) => {
    imageUrls.push(...urls);
    // Continue with your code using the populated imageUrls array
    // ...
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.error('Error fetching image URLs:', error);
  });
```

Here's what the code does:

1. Import the necessary functions from the `firebase/storage` module.
2. Replace `'your-firebase-storage-bucket'` with the name of your Firebase Storage bucket.
3. Create a reference to the folder in your Firebase Storage bucket where your images are stored using `ref(storage, 'path/to/your/folder')`.
4. Use the `listAll` function to get a list of all items (files) in the specified folder.
5. Map over the list of items and use the `getDownloadURL` function to get the download URL for each item (image file).
6. Wait for all the download URLs to be fetched using `Promise.all`.
7. Push the fetched URLs into the `imageUrls` array.
8. After the `imageUrls` array is populated, you can continue with your code using the image URLs.

Make sure to replace `'path/to/your/folder'` with the actual path to the folder in your Firebase Storage bucket where your images are stored.

Note: This code assumes that you have already initialized and configured your Firebase app. If you haven't done that yet, you'll need to follow the Firebase documentation to set up your project and import the necessary Firebase modules.

