HERE IMAGEURL is the same imagein both how do i make it show the next image

To make it show the next image, you need to update the `imageUrl` state or variable with the next image URL. You can achieve this by creating an array of image URLs and keeping track of the current index. Then, you can increment the index when you want to show the next image.

Here's an example of how you can do this in React:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';

const ImageGallery = () => {
  const imageUrls = [
    'https://example.com/image1.jpg',
    'https://example.com/image2.jpg',
    'https://example.com/image3.jpg',
    // Add more image URLs here
  ];

  const [currentIndex, setCurrentIndex] = useState(0);

  const handleNextImage = () => {
    setCurrentIndex((prevIndex) => (prevIndex + 1) % imageUrls.length);
  };

  return (
    <div style={{ display: 'flex', flexWrap: 'wrap', justifyContent: 'center' }}>
      <div
        style={{
          textAlign: 'center',
          width: '100%',
          maxWidth: '300px',
          marginBottom: '20px',
          margin: '0 auto',
        }}
      >
        <span> Face and neck should not be covered.</span>
        <div
          style={{
            width: '100%',
            height: '200px',
            backgroundColor: '#f0f0f0',
            margin: '10px auto',
          }}
        >
          {imageUrls.length > 0 && (
            <img
              src={imageUrls[currentIndex]}
              alt="Face and neck not covered"
              style={{ width: '100%', height: '100%', objectFit: 'cover' }}
            />
          )}
        </div>
        <button onClick={handleNextImage}>Next Image</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default ImageGallery;
```

In this example, we define an array of image URLs called `imageUrls`. We also use the `useState` hook to create a state variable `currentIndex` to keep track of the current index of the image being displayed.

The `handleNextImage` function is called when the "Next Image" button is clicked. It updates the `currentIndex` state by incrementing it by 1 and taking the modulus with the length of the `imageUrls` array. This ensures that the index wraps around to 0 when it reaches the end of the array.

In the JSX code, we use the `imageUrls[currentIndex]` to display the current image URL in the `<img>` tag. We also add a button with an `onClick` handler that calls the `handleNextImage` function.

When you click the "Next Image" button, the `currentIndex` state will be updated, and the next image URL from the `imageUrls` array will be displayed in the `<img>` tag.

Note that this example assumes you're using React. If you're not using React, you can achieve a similar result by manipulating the DOM directly using JavaScript.

    useEffect(() =&gt; {

        fetchImageUrls();
        const storage = getStorage();
        const imageRef = ref(storage, &quot;/home/1.jpg&quot;);

        getDownloadURL(imageRef)
            .then((url) =&gt; {
                setImageUrl(url);
            })
            .catch((error) =&gt; {
                console.error(&quot;Error getting samples download URL:&quot;, error);
            });
    }, []);

i wanna be able to show other images like 2.png 3.png here. How do i do that?

To show other images like `2.png`, `3.png`, etc., you can create an array of image references and iterate through them. Here's how you can modify your code:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import { getStorage, ref, getDownloadURL } from 'firebase/storage';

const ImageGallery = () => {
  const [imageUrls, setImageUrls] = useState([]);
  const [currentIndex, setCurrentIndex] = useState(0);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchImages = async () => {
      const storage = getStorage();
      const imageRefs = [
        ref(storage, '/home/1.jpg'),
        ref(storage, '/home/2.png'),
        ref(storage, '/home/3.png'),
        // Add more image references here
      ];

      const urls = await Promise.all(
        imageRefs.map((imageRef) => getDownloadURL(imageRef))
      );

      setImageUrls(urls);
    };

    fetchImages();
  }, []);

  const handleNextImage = () => {
    setCurrentIndex((prevIndex) => (prevIndex + 1) % imageUrls.length);
  };

  return (
    <div style={{ display: 'flex', flexWrap: 'wrap', justifyContent: 'center' }}>
      <div
        style={{
          textAlign: 'center',
          width: '100%',
          maxWidth: '300px',
          marginBottom: '20px',
          margin: '0 auto',
        }}
      >
        <span> Face and neck should not be covered.</span>
        <div
          style={{
            width: '100%',
            height: '200px',
            backgroundColor: '#f0f0f0',
            margin: '10px auto',
          }}
        >
          {imageUrls.length > 0 && (
            <img
              src={imageUrls[currentIndex]}
              alt="Face and neck not covered"
              style={{ width: '100%', height: '100%', objectFit: 'cover' }}
            />
          )}
        </div>
        <button onClick={handleNextImage}>Next Image</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default ImageGallery;
```

In this updated code:

1. We create a new state variable `imageUrls` to store an array of image URLs.
2. Inside the `useEffect` hook, we define a new async function `fetchImages`.
3. Inside `fetchImages`, we create an array of image references `imageRefs` using the `ref` function from `firebase/storage`. You can add more image references to this array.
4. We use `Promise.all` and `map` to get the download URLs for all the image references in the `imageRefs` array.
5. We set the `imageUrls` state with the array of download URLs using `setImageUrls(urls)`.
6. In the JSX code, we use `imageUrls[currentIndex]` to display the current image URL in the `<img>` tag.

With this approach, you can add more image references to the `imageRefs` array, and they will be fetched and displayed in the image gallery. The "Next Image" button will cycle through all the images in the `imageUrls` array.

Note: Make sure to import the necessary functions (`ref`, `getDownloadURL`) from `firebase/storage` at the top of the file.

If you want to hardcode the image URLs instead of fetching them from Firebase Storage, you can modify the code as follows:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';

const ImageGallery = () => {
  const imageUrls = [
    'https://example.com/1.jpg',
    'https://example.com/2.png',
    'https://example.com/3.png',
    // Add more image URLs here
  ];

  const [currentIndex, setCurrentIndex] = useState(0);

  const handleNextImage = () => {
    setCurrentIndex((prevIndex) => (prevIndex + 1) % imageUrls.length);
  };

  return (
    <div style={{ display: 'flex', flexWrap: 'wrap', justifyContent: 'center' }}>
      <div
        style={{
          textAlign: 'center',
          width: '100%',
          maxWidth: '300px',
          marginBottom: '20px',
          margin: '0 auto',
        }}
      >
        <span> Face and neck should not be covered.</span>
        <div
          style={{
            width: '100%',
            height: '200px',
            backgroundColor: '#f0f0f0',
            margin: '10px auto',
          }}
        >
          {imageUrls.length > 0 && (
            <img
              src={imageUrls[currentIndex]}
              alt="Face and neck not covered"
              style={{ width: '100%', height: '100%', objectFit: 'cover' }}
            />
          )}
        </div>
        <button onClick={handleNextImage}>Next Image</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default ImageGallery;
```

In this modified code:

1. We define an array of image URLs called `imageUrls` directly inside the `ImageGallery` component.
2. We remove the `useEffect` hook and the code related to fetching images from Firebase Storage since we're hardcoding the URLs.
3. The rest of the code remains the same, where we use `imageUrls[currentIndex]` to display the current image URL in the `<img>` tag, and the "Next Image" button cycles through the `imageUrls` array.

You can add or modify the URLs in the `imageUrls` array to include the desired image URLs. For example:

```jsx
const imageUrls = [
  'https://example.com/1.jpg',
  'https://example.com/2.png',
  'https://example.com/3.png',
  'https://example.com/4.jpg',
  'https://example.com/5.png',
];
```

With this approach, you don't need to fetch the image URLs from Firebase Storage, and the image gallery will display the hardcoded URLs in the order they are defined in the `imageUrls` array.

