After making this change, the text "Clear and Face" will be displayed for all the images in the frontend.

To display different names for each image, you can modify the code to use an array of names instead of a single string. Here's how you can do it:

1. Create an array of names you want to display for each image. For example:

```jsx
const imageNames = ['Clear Face', 'Variety in Background', 'Different Clothing', 'Single Person', 'Uncovered Face'];
```

2. Modify the JSX code to use the `imageNames` array and map over it along with the `homeImageUrls` object:

```jsx
<div style={{ display: 'flex', flexWrap: 'wrap', justifyContent: 'center' }}>
  {Object.entries(homeImageUrls).map(([imageName, url], index) => (
    <div
      key={imageName}
      style={{
        textAlign: 'center',
        width: '100%',
        maxWidth: '300px',
        marginBottom: '20px',
        margin: '0 auto',
      }}
    >
      <span> {imageNames[index]}</span>
      <div
        style={{
          width: '100%',
          height: '300px',
          backgroundColor: '#f0f0f0',
          margin: '10px auto',
        }}
      >
        {url && (
          <img
            src={url}
            alt={imageName}
            style={{ width: '100%', height: '100%', objectFit: 'cover' }}
          />
        )}
      </div>
    </div>
  ))}
</div>
```

In this updated code, we're using the `index` parameter from the `map` function to access the corresponding name from the `imageNames` array.

Make sure to add the `imageNames` array at the top of your component:

```jsx
const imageNames = ['Clear Face', 'Variety in Background', 'Different Clothing', 'Single Person', 'Uncovered Face'];

function Headshot() {
  // ...
}
```

With this change, each image will have a different name displayed based on the `imageNames` array.

