CHECK THIS FILE, CAN YOU DISPLAY &quot;errormessage&quot; the one from seterrormessage to the user on the page? I want it to display (if the user uploads less than 5 images or more than 20)

Sure, you can display the `errorMessage` to the user on the page by adding a conditional rendering for an error message component or element. Here's an example of how you can modify the code to achieve this:

```jsx
<Container className="headshot-container d-flex align-items-center justify-content-center text-center">
    {/* ... */}

    <Card className="upload-card my-4" style={{ width: '100%', maxWidth: '800px', borderRadius: '25px' }}>
        <Card.Body>
            <Card.Title className="mb-4">Upload Images</Card.Title>
            {/* Added spacing */}
            <div style={{ marginBottom: '1rem' }}></div>
            {/* Display error message if present */}
            {errorMessage && (
                <Alert variant="danger" className="text-center">
                    {errorMessage}
                </Alert>
            )}
            {/* ... */}
        </Card.Body>
    </Card>

    {/* ... */}
</Container>
```

In the above code, we added a conditional rendering for an `Alert` component from `react-bootstrap` inside the `Card` component where the file upload happens. If `errorMessage` has a value (i.e., not an empty string), it will render the `Alert` component with the `variant="danger"` prop, which will display the error message in a red alert box.

You can style the `Alert` component further by adding additional CSS classes or inline styles as per your requirements.

Alternatively, if you prefer not to use the `Alert` component from `react-bootstrap`, you can create a custom error message element using regular HTML and CSS. For example:

```jsx
{errorMessage && (
    <div className="error-message text-center text-danger mb-3">
        {errorMessage}
    </div>
)}
```

This will render a `div` element with the `error-message` class and the `text-center`, `text-danger`, and `mb-3` (margin-bottom) utility classes from Bootstrap when `errorMessage` is not an empty string. You can then style the `.error-message` class in your CSS file to customize the appearance of the error message.

To show a message when not all checkboxes are checked, you can add a condition to check if all checkboxes are checked before allowing the form submission. Here's how you can modify the code:

```jsx
// ...

const handleSubmit = async (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    const allChecked = checkboxes.every(Boolean); // Check if all checkboxes are true

    if (!allChecked) {
        setShowError(true);
        return;
    }

    if (selectedFiles.length < 5) {
        setErrorMessage('Please select at least 5 images.');
        return;
    }

    if (selectedFiles.length > 20) {
        setErrorMessage('You can upload a maximum of 20 images.');
        return;
    }

    // ...
};

// ...

<Card className="upload-card my-4" style={{ width: '100%', maxWidth: '800px', borderRadius: '25px' }}>
    <Card.Body>
        <Card.Title className="mb-4">Upload Images</Card.Title>
        {/* Added spacing */}
        <div style={{ marginBottom: '1rem' }}></div>
        {/* Display error message if present */}
        {errorMessage && (
            <Alert variant="danger" className="text-center">
                {errorMessage}
            </Alert>
        )}
        {/* Display checkbox error message if showError is true */}
        {showError && (
            <Alert variant="danger" className="text-center">
                Checkboxes must all be checked
            </Alert>
        )}
        {/* ... */}
    </Card.Body>
</Card>

// ...
```

In the modified code:

1. We added a new state variable `showError` and initialized it to `false`.
2. In the `handleSubmit` function, we first check if all checkboxes are checked using the `every` method on the `checkboxes` array. If not all checkboxes are checked, we set `showError` to `true` and return from the function.
3. Inside the `Card` component, we added a new conditional rendering for an `Alert` component that displays the message "Checkboxes must all be checked" when `showError` is `true`.

Now, when the user tries to submit the form without checking all the checkboxes, the "Checkboxes must all be checked" message will be displayed. If all checkboxes are checked but there are other issues (like not enough images selected or too many images selected), the corresponding error message will be displayed instead.

Note: You might also want to reset the `showError` state when the user starts checking the checkboxes again or when the form is successfully submitted.

