To stylize the "Choose Files" button with the color 'appTheme', you can use the `useTheme` hook from `@mui/material/styles` and access the theme colors. Here's how you can modify your code:

```jsx
import { Form } from 'react-bootstrap';
import { useTheme } from '@mui/material/styles';

const YourComponent = () => {
    const theme = useTheme();

    return (
        <div className="d-flex flex-column align-items-center mb-3">
            <Form.Group controlId="formFile">
                <Form.Label
                    className="custom-file-upload"
                    style={{
                        backgroundColor: theme.palette.appTheme.main,
                        color: 'white',
                        padding: '8px 16px',
                        borderRadius: '4px',
                        cursor: 'pointer',
                    }}
                >
                    <i className="fas fa-cloud-upload-alt me-2"></i>
                    Choose Files
                    <Form.Control
                        type="file"
                        onChange={onImageSelect}
                        multiple
                        accept="image/*"
                        className="d-none"
                    />
                </Form.Label>
                {selectedFiles.length > 0 && (
                    <span className="text-white">{selectedFiles.length} images selected</span>
                )}
            </Form.Group>
        </div>
    );
};
```

In this updated code:

1. We import the `useTheme` hook from `@mui/material/styles`.
2. Inside the component, we call the `useTheme` hook to get the current theme object.
3. We apply an inline `style` prop to the `<Form.Label>` element, which represents the "Choose Files" button.
4. In the `style` object, we set the `backgroundColor` to `theme.palette.appTheme.main`, which will use the main color of the `appTheme` palette from your theme configuration.
5. We also set the `color` to `'white'` for better contrast with the background color.
6. Additionally, we add some padding, border-radius, and cursor styles to make the button look more like a button.

Make sure that you have defined the `appTheme` color in your theme configuration. If you're using the default Material-UI theme, you can extend it and add the `appTheme` color to the `palette` object.

For example, if you're using a custom theme file (`theme.js`), you can add the `appTheme` color like this:

```jsx
import { createTheme } from '@mui/material/styles';

const theme = createTheme({
    palette: {
        appTheme: {
            main: '#35004E', // Replace with your desired color
        },
        // Other palette colors...
    },
    // Other theme configurations...
});

export default theme;
```

In this example, we're adding the `appTheme` color with the value `#35004E`. You can replace it with your desired color value.

After defining the `appTheme` color in your theme configuration, the "Choose Files" button will use that color when you access it via `theme.palette.appTheme.main`.

